We wish to \emph{minimize} the \textbf{cost}, C, subject to the
constraint that the length of the base is twice it's width and that the
volume of the container must be $V = 8 \text{m}^{3}$.

\includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{../json_data/MATH104/December_2013/MATH104_December2013_Question04.jpg}

The cost C can be expressed as the sum of the costs for all the sides.
Recall that this is an open-top box (i.e., no top). If we let \emph{l},
\emph{w}, and \emph{h} denote the length, width, and height of the box
in metres, respectively, then:

\begin{align*}
C &= C_{\text{sides}} + C_{\text{bottom}} \\
&= 6 (2hw + 2hl) + 4.5(lw)
\end{align*}

since material for the base costs \textbackslash{}\$4.50 per square
metre, and material for the sides costs \textbackslash{}\$6 per square
metre.

We are also given the constraint

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle V = lwh = 8
\end{align*} Using the fact that the length is twice
the width (i.e., \emph{l = 2w}), the cost function and volume constraint
are expressed as

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle C = 36hw + 9w^{2}, \quad V = 2w^{2}h = 8
\end{align*}

To reduce this into a single variable problem, we use the constraint to
express the \emph{height} of the box \emph{in terms of the width}:

\begin{align*}
h = \frac{4}{w^{2}},
\end{align*} and substitute this into the cost function
\emph{C}, making it a function of \emph{w} only:

\begin{align*}
C(w) = \frac{144}{w} + 9w^{2}
\end{align*}

To optimize C, we determine first determine its critical points by
differentiating with respect to \emph{w} and setting the derivative
equal to zero:

\begin{align*}
C'(w) &= -\frac{144}{w^{2}} + 18w \\
0 &= -\frac{144}{w^{2}} + 18w \\
144 &= 18w^3 \\
8 &= w^3 \\
w &= 2
\end{align*}

Therefore \emph{w} = 2 is a critical point. To determine whether or not
it is the point that minimizes \emph{C}, we use the \textbf{second
derivative test}. The second derivative of C with respect to w is

\begin{align*}
C''(w) = \frac{288}{w^{3}} + 18
\end{align*} which is clearly greater than zero
when \emph{w} = 2. Thus, by the second derivative test, \emph{C} has a
local minimum at \emph{w} = 2 (Moreover, it is the \emph{global minimum}
since there are no other critical points.) Substituting \emph{w} = 2
into the cost function, we determine that the minimum cost is

\begin{align*}
C(2) = \frac{144}{2} + 9(2)^{2} = 72 + 36 = {\color{blue}\$108}
\end{align*}
